q04_other_fear: In the shelter, he barked and barked and flung drool across his snout, and panted and whined really hard, constantly.  He was very worked up the entire time in the kennel/shelter.  He was like that when first arriving home, though not quite to that degree because it's quieter here and he got to get out, rather than being stuck behind bars. But I drugged him at night so we could all sleep.  He gets anxious walking past other dogs still, but is not longer barking and lunging at them, but rather now knows to make eye contact with me.  He's good in the car.  I got to the end of this and you don't ask how he is now.  He's a normal dog now, with me.  He gets wound up with new people, but can calm down and lie quietly while they are here. He barks at the doorbell.  He barks when people pass by the window.  He lives with 3 other dogs and a cat (one dog and the cat have since died), which other "experts" have said could never happen.  I worked with him at the shelter for about 2-3 months (?) before getting him out of there and then brought him home where he could become sane and not be treated with punishment, but rather de-stress and learn how to calm and be normal.  He can still get snippy occasionally when one of my dogs gets too close (when something else exciting is going on, like strangers walking past the window and they're both barking), because the Roomba bumped them together once, but for the most part he is a normal, sweet, loving, smart little guy.  He loved the cat!  I was told by an "expert" he could never be near a cat.  In the 2 years since I've met him I have become a certified trainer in my own right, and the positive consistent methods have worked wonders with him.  He was going to be put down by the shelter but by then he and I had become close, so I couldn't let that happen.

As in many surveys, it felt like the whole story couldn't be told so the answers were disingenuous. Two of my four (Asta and Phin) had aggression issues that were largely medically based (Asta has a severely compromised thyroid and Phin had an undiagnosed heart condition causing exercise intolerance which manifested over time in biting us to prevent leashing for walks that made him uncomfortable). In the end we did a lot of things with and for them but their thyroid supplement and pimobendin (vetmedin) made all the difference. The one I really treated for behavior was Timber because his resource guarding was unlivable. Asta is the most managed. Bert is the most annoying, and Phin is basically perfect. Also, people's response to their dogs' aggression is not isolated. If a dog is aloof and aggressive v affectionate/social with the same level of aggression, the response of the guardian is likely to be quite different. All of my dogs have a ton of great qualities that outweigh the behavior challenges and motivate me to work with them and put up with them.

feedback_extra_2: I have rescued Pitbulls before but I have to say Jada is the hardest dog I have trained. She has to think about stuff for a while before she gets it. One example I was training her to shake, for about 3-4 weeks I tried everyday about 3 times a day, she never got it. So I had given up and quit training her to shake. I figured shaking wasn't all that important if she shaked or not. About 3-4 weeks later just out of the blue she sat in front of me and picked her paw up to shake. I was like OMG she finally got it. It's like she had to sleep on it and "stew" over it to figure it out. She is like that with a lot things, it takes her a little bit of time but she eventually figures it out.The normal everyday training just doesn't work with her she just doesn't respond. Part of the problem with trying to train her is she has the worst case of doggy ADD I have ever seen. Best example I can give is I will take her out to poop and she will finally find the perfect spot,get in the position and start to poop, then something will catch her eye (a bird flying or squirrel will run out a tree or a neighbors dog starts to bark etc.) she will literally stop pooping . (I personally don't even know how it's possible to stop a poop when it starts to come out). And to top it all off she will then forget she even had to poop.It will take her another 45min to an hour to get re- focused to even poop. I could have a steak in my had and she still wouldn't focus.It's one thing for a small puppy to do that but I have never seen it this bad in a adult dog. Over all she has done better in some areas than I expected and is much slower in other areas than a "normal" dog would be. When we first got her she would have horrible nightmares every time she slept. Now they are far and few so that is a positive sign I think.

behavior_tech_other: Clementine's major behavorial issue when we adopted her (a little over 1 year ago) was voiding in the house. We understood that having spent her entire life in a kennel from the time of her rescue from a hoarding case at 8 weeks to when we adopted her at the age of two, just being in a house was going to be stressful for her. Unfortunately in her case, clicker training was not really an option, both because the sound was stressful and because she was so shut down from the stress that our only goal in the first year was acclimating the two of them to living closely with people in a home environment.When Clem did not want to go outside to use the bathroom, the only way to get her to go out was to carry her to the yard. Our schedule was very different from the rescue's schedule, of course, so establishing a new one was possibly confusing for them. Later on after she mastered going outside, Clemmie's sister, Pippi, would also 'assist' in getting Clemmie out.  We adopted both of them together. They are genetic siblings and the same age. Pippi did this by sniffing Clem's urethra, offering play signals and running out the back door, and even walking behind Clementine and trying to 'nudge' her from a sitting position into a standing position. Our house is configured so that Pippi and Clem have to pass through three doorways in two rooms to get into our large, fenced-in yard. (The size of the yard is probably a little bit stressful for these two, and so is the street noise. They like to go out in the dead of night and run around.) Passing through the gate, dutch door, or backdoor are part of the ritual of going outside now, too. Both of them get loads of verbal praise, touch, and a treat when they go outside. (They've both progressed to a point where they constantly and actively solicit physical contact. Clem is especially cuddly.)While Clem does have the patellar luxation, cauda equina syndrome, and hip dysplasia, she loves taking walks in a nearby National Park and her condition is well managed. The relative discomfort she feels from the patellar issue might cause her to delay going outside, but we don't believe it was the entire reason she was reluctant in the beginning of our relationship together. Clem is on a protocol of Adequan injections - which we administer once monthly at home - until our Vet tells us it's time for her first surgery. Clementine and Pippi both eat a high quality diet (Earthborn Holistic grain free fish formula) that helps manage skin conditions and Clementine's musculo-skeletal issues. They also get Omegas and Osteo True Benefits (both from Veterinary Recommended Solutions) in their food. They seem less mentally sluggish than they did when we adopted them - their diets could play a role. They look to us to figure out situations, they respond to our conversation, and they're tuned in.

behavior_tech_other: leadership protocol: not on owner's bed, follow owner through narrow spaces, move out of owner's way, owner initiates interactions, owner greets visitors before dog, dog walks behind owner in stressful situations. I used a prong collar to train the last behavior. I used perhaps a dozen jerks to establish the behavior in the first week. After a month we returned to a martingale collar (to prevent him slipping out of the collar since he has a small head), walking behind was by then on cue and we were and are able to walk pass dogs and cats he  would previously have reacted to. I observe that he sometimes will voluntarily move behind me. When he does that I frequently see a dog I hadn't noticed

desc_other_equip: Mostly my hands - to move him to the space, or illustrate the movement, or use gentle pressure. Which is not equipment per say, but that's mostly what I use. :)
behavior_tech_other: I occasionally use negative punishment followed by a directive or positive reinforcement for more serious issues (not basic obedience like sit, stay (as asked on the first page)) but barking too much and ignoring a command, biting (almost never a problem), not listening (after ample chances). The other method is time out (being put in a room, or area away from us, for a few minutes to show a behavior was unacceptable).
behavior_other_best: If he *is* going to have an issue with something (he has very few issues in general - usually something like barking excessively at dogs walking by, or begging too much), what works best is a combo of positive reinforcement and negative reinforcement, and communication. (I know neg. is largely not accepted. I'm careful to balance it, make sure it's having the desired effect, and never train out of anger, but feign it if need be.) He really does do best with a mix of the two. :) For specific issues (where punishment would be confusing, and positive reinforcing), time out works best. For training to walk nicely on the leash, it's all about communication and finding a happy medium. :) A retractable leash was a lifesaver there - he knows exactly how long it goes, not to pull, but he's free to explore, unless I do a recall or wait and ask him to sit for a passing car. We're still working on him letting my family play with my hair, or jokingly poke me, etc. without him worrying... this is pretty much his only unsolved issue (prob bc we have the least amount of chances to work on it).
feedback_extra_2: It would have been helpful to know more about what sort of issues I was saying got better or not to make sure I was being accurate :) - I didn't remember my original responses. And a lot of these issues, aren't really issues. Like yeah, they happen, but they're not a problem, we work through them. He's rarely exposed to other dogs, and when he is, we give him a little coaching, he starts talking with the other pup and he's good. Or, him jumping on people, we tell him not to, and he's good. Or him rolling in stuff XD Haha, he might have to get a bath, but it's the joy of life for him to do so, so that is so not a "problem", but it happens. The only issue is him being over protective of me; and when he hasn't had a lot of people come in, he's getting more barky at people in the home. The second one we work on, and he's good within a few corrections. The first has been an impossibility we work on whenever we can. Anyways, I know there's a giant spectrum of owners, but absolutely none of these are really issue for us - and gaw, I'd never never give him up for anything (but I know people do, I used to work in a shelter). Also, I was hoping to be able to clarify which were problems, and which were 1. already dealt with (like separation anxiety - we came up with a plan and it was solved) 2. not considered a problem with us, and 3. ongoing but dealt with by ___. For his separation anxiety, we began to leave him uncrated, give him 2 windows to look out of, and leave music on, leave without stress, and give him a treat. It took a couple times for him to get used to it, and a couple mildly chewed pillows/curtains (and subsequent time out - this dog, man, never ceases to amaze me - he really did know what the time out was for, and he comes with me every time jumping on the futon he's allowed to get on while we're gone and wagging like "See how good I did!?" and if he was good [which is 99% of the time], he gets petted right away, and no time out). I took him to a group puppy class and sure it "worked" (it trained him with a 'choke' collar) but he didn't know what was happening half the time. I abandoned most of those concepts soon after, and tried and failed many other ways of training, until we settled on the current set up. Flat collar, harness, flexi-leash (or short leash for city and busy zones), communication, incentive, time out, and occasional spanks when something's REALLY wrong. I always check him after a neg punishment, to make sure he understands what's going on and it hasn't hurt his spirit at all. Mainly, we just talk with him, tell him what we need, and he lives life with us (going to the R/C club, camping, road trips, being on bed with me when I work from home, etc.) - people always say I've trained him so well, but I think a lot of it is him, the exposure he has to so many different things, my entire family treating him like a part of the family, and he just understands a lot of stuff!! :D

I wasn't sure if I was supposed to answer what we did to train Roxy when she was little, or what we have done recently to try to stop her from jumping on people.  So I included both techniques from when she was little and also techniques we use now.  The main thing that works right now is to reinforce "sit" and "off" as soon as someone approaches, but if she jumps on them anyway we jerk the leash.  When she was a puppy we tried ignoring it, re-directing, leash jerks, reinforcing "sit" etc and the only thing that worked was physically stopping her from jumping up by stepping on the leash on the ground so that it was so short she couldn't jump up.  I also want to say that ignoring bad behavior to extinguish it might work for some dogs, but definitely not for Roxy because she was very strong willed and persistent when she was young.  She is now a lovely, well behaved dog, but she still has to be reminded constantly to not jump on visitors.  I think part of the problem is that some people pet her for it even though I tell them not to.  Thank you for doing this research.

Had been left at NYC shelter two weeks before I got her. Was very nervous over-all, hyper friendly to everyone, never seemed able to just 'relax' in the home or out on walks. On walks would only focus on me and would never leave my side to explore or sniff things. That has changed drastically, took about six months. She is much calmer now in the home and everywhere we go, and is happy to go for off-leash walks and wander from me (up to about 15 yards) to explore and smell things she is interested in. desc_other_equip: She's really not highly problematic. She is an 8lb, 12 year old Yorkie-Dachshund mix that I adopted at age ten. When I first got her she was fearful of other dogs and would bark at them. She's on a "Puppia" harness for walking and she's gradually learned with me over 18 months that not all other dogs are "scary". I made sure she only encounters, up-close, dogs I know who will be calm and gentle with her, and she now tentatively goes up to new dogs after looking to me for confirmation and will nose boop them and say hello. Much calmer around all dogs in general, actually has a couple of dog "friends" now who she seems to actually like. Will now watch other dogs walk past her at a distance and just gaze, rather than erupt. This was all done with calm, patient reinforcement & treats. No "equipment" per se. She also knows that if there is another dog charging towards her (that I don't personally know) and looks problematic, or a really rambunctious puppy that will stomp all over her I WILL pick her up and get her safely out of the fray. She does not rely on this though and can work the greetings out on her own now with calm dogs. Only other problem is eliminating indoors. She *mostly* uses wee wee pads when inside, but misses a lot. Has finally *mostly* learned to come tell me when she needs to go out, but will often come to let me know AFTER she's gone, is looking for a treat! (she gets rewarded with a treat when she goes OUTSIDE only). Truthfully, a very sweet dog but not the smartest one I've ever met. She tries tho. When she *remembers* she's supposed to pee and poop outside, she does try to let me know. We're about at 50/50 and after 18 months of making myself crazy over it, I've resigned myself to that and wee wee pads. I'm a dog walker and she comes to work with me most days and rides around in the car. Gets multiple opportunities daily to eliminate outside and at least one extended walk off leash on her own every day. She just doesn't seem to understand there is any difference between "going" outside vs. inside. She spent her first ten years in an apt. in NYC and I doubt was ever walked outdoors on any regular basis. I doubt she even got outdoors 1x a day.

My hands were  burned by the leash, knees were covered by scratches and bruises from falling down. We went to a recommended dog trainer, but he suggested to snatch my dog and so on, like Milano does. I felt that these methods are not my choice and founded very gentle and thoughtful dog behavior specialist in internet. Unfortunately in Russia there are no special courses to get a diploma for dog  behavior, all she did - was reading books and practicing. She consulted me once or twice, gave literature (Karen Pryor) and I started to correct first main problem - aggression. It took a month for me to notice the contact with my dog and to have pleasure from the walking with a him. I used BAT to correct the behavior. To solve the problem with eating feces first I changed the diet - past owner fed him very unhealthy. After it, he stopped eating feces, but continued eating anything else, like moldy stuff. I used negative punishment: after Miron ate something, I Just took him back home. Even if it happened before he did his priority needs. I took him home and imitated that the walk is over. Plus he had no food at home. Hour later I took him to do the needs, but only for 5 minutes. It took a week to set the association "Eating feces - go back home immediately". My dog is a re-home; she is now 8 and I got her when she was 6 from a boarding kennel owner where she was a brood bitch (2 litters). She had no problems with urination / defecation in home, once she learned what was wanted (3-4 months). Taught w/positive methods (keep outside, praise when perform; crate when supervision not possible. no aversives upon in-house mistake, just my body language / expression of disapproval. She is very "soft", and responded beautifully to slow, gentle approach. The more serioius, but still mild "problem" related to exposure to other dogs in public, particularly larger ones.  Being a basic coward, she'd do the "gonna get you first" thing, then dart away and often be willing to play upon other dog not taking her seriously.  Her idea of really serious "keep away from me" warning ws to air-snap at other dog with absolutely no intent to bite. The most successful method was "train an incompatible behavior" and "reward reward reward" (food for both). She has always been totally fine with dogs invited into the home, no matter the size.  I limit invitations to the well-behaved, biddable, well-socialized dogs.  "Home = Safety" in her mind, and she trusts me. She still will  not play with toys. She plays one game only, a prey-drive game (chase balloon on a lure pole), asks for it frequently, focuses intently, and is permitted to "kill" the balloon occasionally. She could easily become OCD  were I not aware of the risks.  She's a dream-child compared to the EBTs I so adore, comparable to my Labrador.  Considering her first 6 years of intellectual / emotional deprivation, she's a real success story. We're in the survey as a "normal" control -- i.e. dog w/o serious problems requiring behaviorist intervention.

feedback_extra_2: THE EXPERIMENT (both surveys):As far as the experiment itself, my only comment would be about the details of the experiment. Perhaps a follow-up email about the different parts you answered and need to work on. That way there can be a refresher between each survey, since I found myself confused about some of the questions because I could not recall my answers before (usually a good technique, I know... but when asking about changes that were worked on between surveys it might not hurt to reminds us). Any plans or expectations about how to follow up the first survey (e.g. training options: no training, at home training, professional training, etc.), because I felt like I'd forgotten to do my homework unsure of whether I committed to professional training when I had no intentions of using that unless necessary. And then perhaps small descriptions of how to tackle to training, or at the very least the list of training techniques that was in the second survey, but perhaps with a bit more detail (I had to google "relaxation protocols" since we weren't taught that in ABA and I didn't work with a professional trainer which meant I didn't have access to ever hearing those terms) to assist in the training or at least in understanding the follow up survey.Otherwise, the length was impressive in it's shortness. I felt in some places that my answer required more detail (hence the explanation below), but I can fully appreciate why that couldn't be accomplished in experimental research without becoming too complex (but I still provide the details below in the event that they're of some use or necessary).~ ~ ~MY DOG (Willow):Willow turned 1-year-old on 2/23/2018, therefore she's been in her sensitive phases of puppyhood, making her a bit more malleable learning-wise than what I would have expected from a dog that's reached social maturity. However, during this period she was also going through her juvenile phase and the age range she likely reached sexual maturity (she was spayed at 8-weeks-old), and for part of the time she was also going through the age range that many owners of female Rottweilers (Willow's a mix, about 25% Rottweiler, 25% American Staffordshire Terrier, 12.5% Labrador, 12.5% Beagle, and 25% unknown) is their "terror phase" (which begins anywhere from 9-months-old to 1-year-old), in which they become increasingly stubborn on top of the resistance they're having to new learning from prior learning. Willow began showing signs of this around 8.5-months-old and is still behaving as such at 13-months-old. Her destructive behaviors decrease when exercise is increased. Also the temporary elimination of bones as a safety precaution following an incident involving a fight between her and our other dog that resulted in Willow puncturing the dog's ear and neck/hackles area, resulted in a major increase in destructive behavior that did not decrease until bones were reintroduced. Once bones were brought back, the destructive behavior appeared limited to times of boredom or a need for exercise.Her jumping behavior did begging to decrease following punishment emitted by other persons in the household. It also appeared to be tied to a need for exercise, particularly since punishment is what I'd say is roughly 50% less effective when she possesses built up energy. Also, a positive reinforcement plan was added in which she was invited up by me patting on my belly and saying "up" then moving her into a position with her legs "hugging" my waist or shoulders and pairing it with praising her saying, "Good hugs! Good! Goood hugs!". Eventually I began fading the "up" command out, replacing it with "hugs?". This is still a work in progress. She's still very young and clearly very far from reaching social maturity, however, now 57-lbs, standing not very tall but with a body that's visibly incredibly muscular, painted with clear Rottweiler markings, these two behaviors put her at risk. The stigmas and stereotypes that surround her appearance often lead to people crossing the street, not inviting her places despite inviting other dogs, and behaving in a manner toward her that communicates aversion and avoidance. While it's quite sad seeing people ignore such a sweet and overly friendly dog, especially when you have to watch the dog not be able to understand what caused this response, it's not the most pressing concern. My fear is that people will already have expectations and judgements from their first sight of her alone, which makes behaviors that appear aggressive by demonstrating her strength and high energy and excitement, such as destructive behaviors and jumping, dangerous. When she was only 20-lbs, people had already begun to ignore her and respond to her friendly jumps on them with negativity and judgement, despite her paws barely reaching past their knees while on her hind legs. Other people in our household constantly are strict and unforgiving about her training's progress length and it's imperfections, citing her look causing a bias to others (including themselves, even though that went unspoken). As her owner, an aspiring behaviorist, a dog lover, and a supporter of changing the stigma around "bullied breeds", I feel incredibly responsible for the type of behavior she emits - and because of this, I feel much more responsible for her actions than she is, not just because as a behaviorist and a dog behavior researcher I know that their behavior is a reflection of their owner and their training. But also because I want to make a difference for dogs in the world, particularly "bullied breeds", as well as wanting to make sure that the difference I want to make in which dogs will be judged less, respected more, and have more enjoyable lives, I obviously want my own dog to have, as well as need for her to have in order for my belief in this change to exist.It's a lot of expectation that I've put on myself and none of it on her. Any failures are my own. I try to live by letting a dog be a dog as well as my parenting beliefs in which I believe in letting an individual express themselves within reason (e.g. in ways that do not cause them physical/mental/social harm). Any changes that need to be made should be related to collecting data (which I admit I did not do previously), staying consistent with expectations and rewarding, and getting more exercise.~ ~ ~I hope this has been useful and not a total waste of my time (typing) or yours (reading)! Thank you for including us in your experiment!

feedback_extra_2: Sheldon came back to me as a foster dog after being returned to rescue at our organization's insistence.  He had done well with his adoptive family, but the mother developed an almost pathological attachment to him, wrapping him in a blanket and carrying him around like a toddler.  He became possessive of her and "guarded" her whenever other family members approached.  The mother was unable to change her behavior despite consultations with behaviorists and trainers.  When returned to his original foster home with me, Sheldon's possessiveness extinguished almost immediately:  he received the same positive reinforcement to which he had been accustomed in his initial foster stint, was *never* picked up or carried about, and very quickly re-learned "to be a dog."  He has now been adopted to a new family who committed to continuing the positive training to which he responded well in foster care.  He is doing exceptionally well, with no sign of guarding behaviors.  The family works with the Cornell Vet School practice and the practice is aware of Sheldon's past and prepared to make recommendations should issues resurface.

feedback_extra_2: I think the most important thing is that we each have to be an advocate for our dogs.  I had situations in training contexts where I had to say no to the trainer, no I won't ask my dog to do that, or no, he's past his limit and we're going home.   Secondly, we need to remember that each dog is an individual, requiring unique solutions, especially rescue dogs, whose pasts we can only guess about.  My reactive dog gets overly excited with the clicker (loves it), and remains calm when we don't use it, when I mark behavior verbally in a soft voice "good boy".  My fearful dog was apparently punished in a bad training context and is afraid of the clicker, and even afraid of the padded floor of any training facility, so she only does group classes that are group hikes outdoors, where no one is using a clicker, but the dogs are socializing and practicing giving space to joggers and bikes, while receiving lots of yummy treats.  My athletic dog feels safest learning to socialize with other dogs in a sports context, focusing on agility in a class with familiar dogs.   He's learned to trust them just because of their presence week after week, enjoying agility together.    Three completely different solutions for three unique dogs.  Thank you for your interest, and for all you're doing to enrich the human-dog connection and to save dogs' lives via human education.

I'm embarrassed to say that I don't recall which issue I wrote about in the first survey as it related to Connor - there have been quite a few. Connor has severe sensitivity to many foods and his allergies were undoubtedly making him uncomfortable. He is also very fearful of any items leaning against a wall or on the floor space he usually travels and he quickly develops triggers associated with past "traumas" e.g. he won't go down stairs he has used for years because recently a broom fell across the stairs as he was beginning to descend. Because Connor is somewhat of a fearful dog he is keen on deferring to me in most situations which cause him stress and we move quickly through situations which used to be problematic. For my part I've gotten better at learning what will cause him stress and I use habituation with lots of praise and lovely, smelly, treats to encourage him to push through. During play with other dogs he can be too enthusiastic and sometimes even a bit of a bully but will stand down quickly with a short "stop it". feedback_extra_2: As in many surveys, it felt like the whole story couldn't be told so the answers were disingenuous. Two of my four (Asta and Phin) had aggression issues that were largely medically based (Asta has a severely compromised thyroid and Phin had an undiagnosed heart condition causing exercise intolerance which manifested over time in biting us to prevent leashing for walks that made him uncomfortable). In the end we did a lot of things with and for them but their thyroid supplement and pimobendin (vetmedin) made all the difference. The one I really treated for behavior was Timber because his resource guarding was unlivable. Asta is the most managed. Bert is the most annoying, and Phin is basically perfect. Also, people's response to their dogs' aggression is not isolated. If a dog is aloof and aggressive v affectionate/social with the same level of aggression, the response of the guardian is likely to be quite different. All of my dogs have a ton of great qualities that outweigh the behavior challenges and motivate me to work with them and put up with them.

Miley has such high prey drive I had to quit obedience because if she were off leash when another dog chased its dumbbell, she would go after the other dog as if it were a rabbit.  Scary. I control my dogs with whatever tools I need (leash jerk, lure with food, put into a sit, turn away from the stimulus, avoid situations) but I doubt they will ever be dog friendly. German Shepherds are not cocker spaniels or basset hounds.  They are alert, vigilant  and think they own the world. Another repetitive behaviour: He has a specific place in the backyard where he barks. Normally while his sister Emma runs around like a crazed lunatic, Pippin sits back with his toy, quietly wagging his tail. He only goes to that certain spot to bark when he's in a particularly good mood. Another repetitive behaviour: Pippin enjoys knocking ALL of the pillows off the couch on a regular basis. He has this routine where he starts with he smaller pillows and moves his way up to the larger ones.  Another repetitive behaviour that happens many times a day (I have observed this countless times): When my husband goes into the basement to use the washroom, both Pippin and Emma stand frozen in front of their kennel. As soon as the toilet flushes, Pippin opens the kennel door with his paw and both dogs enter as my husband comes up the stairs. They stick their noses out the kennel door awaiting a treat. When we crate trained them as puppies during toilet training, they learned that if they went into their kennel/crate they got a treat. We no longer use the crate (as they can be trusted in the house now that they are adults) but they have "trained" my husband to give them treats in this particular situation.Another repetitive behaviour: When we let Pippin outside into the backyard, he always has to take a toy outside with him and he always has to bring a toy in (and it's not always th me same toy). feedback_extra_2: I found the survey to be a little irrelevant, as most of these "problem" behaviours happened as puppies and young dogs and so the improvement times were basically guesses on my part. I found the final question of the survey to be blunt and horrifying, as I would never surrender my dogs. I work with our dogs with clicker training, treats and lots of praise on a semi-regular basis (positive reinforcement training). I love our dogs like family, so most of their various quirks aren't considered to be "problem behaviour," just "poodle stuff." Pippin hasn't urinated or defecated in the house in years, and the only problem behaviour he has is barking at the window at pedestrians and beg-barking at us to go outside. Emma's only problems are resource guariding (against Pippin only) and barking in the yard. I respect them and love them as an intelligent, highly successful species that we share our home and planet with. But the way, I thought this was a longevity study. Why aren't there more questions about diet, nutrition, feeding style, frequency of feeding, exercise, health and longevity? Why no tips on helping our dogs to live longer based on your research? Training to mitigate problem behaviour is good and all but doesn't feel relevant to the study.

I had situations in training contexts where I had to say no to the trainer, no I won't ask my dog to do that, or no, he's past his limit and we're going home.   Secondly, we need to remember that each dog is an individual, requiring unique solutions, especially rescue dogs, whose pasts we can only guess about.  My reactive dog gets overly excited with the clicker (loves it), and remains calm when we don't use it, when I mark behavior verbally in a soft voice "good boy".  My fearful dog was apparently punished in a bad training context and is afraid of the clicker, and even afraid of the padded floor of any training facility, so she only does group classes that are group hikes outdoors, where no one is using a clicker, but the dogs are socializing and practicing giving space to joggers and bikes, while receiving lots of yummy treats.  My athletic dog feels safest learning to socialize with other dogs in a sports context, focusing on agility in a class with familiar dogs.   He's learned to trust them just because of their presence week after week, enjoying agility together.    Three completely different solutions for three unique dogs.  Thank you for your interest, and for all you're doing to enrich the human-dog connection and to save dogs' lives via human education.

feedback_extra_2: I think the most important thing is that we each have to be an advocate for our dogs.  I had situations in training contexts where I had to say no to the trainer, no I won't ask my dog to do that, or no, he's past his limit and we're going home.   Secondly, we need to remember that each dog is an individual, requiring unique solutions, especially rescue dogs, whose pasts we can only guess about.  My reactive dog gets overly excited with the clicker (loves it), and remains calm when we don't use it, when I mark behavior verbally in a soft voice "good boy".  My fearful dog was apparently punished in a bad training context and is afraid of the clicker, and even afraid of the padded floor of any training facility, so she only does group classes that are group hikes outdoors, where no one is using a clicker, but the dogs are socializing and practicing giving space to joggers and bikes, while receiving lots of yummy treats.  My athletic dog feels safest learning to socialize with other dogs in a sports context, focusing on agility in a class with familiar dogs.   He's learned to trust them just because of their presence week after week, enjoying agility together.    Three completely different solutions for three unique dogs.  Thank you for your interest, and for all you're doing to enrich the human-dog connection and to save dogs' lives via human education.

feedback_extra_2: As in many surveys, it felt like the whole story couldn't be told so the answers were disingenuous. Two of my four (Asta and Phin) had aggression issues that were largely medically based (Asta has a severely compromised thyroid and Phin had an undiagnosed heart condition causing exercise intolerance which manifested over time in biting us to prevent leashing for walks that made him uncomfortable). In the end we did a lot of things with and for them but their thyroid supplement and pimobendin (vetmedin) made all the difference. The one I really treated for behavior was Timber because his resource guarding was unlivable. Asta is the most managed. Bert is the most annoying, and Phin is basically perfect. Also, people's response to their dogs' aggression is not isolated. If a dog is aloof and aggressive v affectionate/social with the same level of aggression, the response of the guardian is likely to be quite different. All of my dogs have a ton of great qualities that outweigh the behavior challenges and motivate me to work with them and put up with them.
For the most part Grissom's issues are fear based and the biggest help for him  was knowing that my husband and I  would be  there to protect him from what scared him.
